    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is berberine as effective as metformin for blood sugar?</summary>
      <p>A 2008 study showed comparable HbA1c reduction (berberine -0.9% vs metformin -1.0%). However, this was one study with 116 patients. Metformin has 5,000+ clinical trials with millions of patients. Berberine shows promise but does not have the same evidence depth to be considered a proven equivalent.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I take berberine instead of metformin?</summary>
      <p>This decision must be made with your physician. Metformin is FDA-approved with decades of safety data. Berberine is a supplement. For diagnosed type 2 diabetes, replacing metformin with berberine without medical oversight could be dangerous. For prediabetes, discuss berberine with your healthcare provider first.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How do berberine and metformin work differently?</summary>
      <p>Both activate AMPK but through different pathways. Metformin inhibits mitochondrial Complex I. Berberine activates AMPK through multiple pathways plus modulates gut microbiome and bile acid metabolism. Berberine also significantly affects lipid metabolism, which metformin does not.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I take berberine and metformin together?</summary>
      <p>Only under physician supervision. Both lower blood sugar, and combining them increases hypoglycemia risk. Both cause GI side effects that may amplify when combined. Some physicians prescribe this combination at adjusted doses based on individual patient profiles. Never combine without medical approval.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Why is berberine called Nature's Ozempic?</summary>
      <p>A TikTok marketing label, not a pharmacological comparison. Ozempic (semaglutide) is a GLP-1 agonist that produces 10-15% body weight loss. Berberine activates AMPK and produces 2-3% weight loss. They work through completely different mechanisms. The magnitude of effect is vastly different.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What are the side effects of each?</summary>
      <p>Both cause GI symptoms (diarrhea, bloating, cramps). Metformin: rare lactic acidosis risk, B12 depletion long-term. Berberine: inhibits CYP3A4/CYP2D6 enzymes, creating drug interaction risks with ~50% of prescription medications. Less long-term safety data than metformin.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is berberine FDA approved?</summary>
      <p>No. Berberine is a dietary supplement regulated under DSHEA, not an FDA-approved drug. It has not undergone Phase I-III clinical trials for FDA approval. Manufacturing standards vary between brands. This does not mean it is ineffective, but the regulatory and evidence frameworks differ significantly from metformin.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Who should consider berberine supplementation?</summary>
